tes at the dog park, regular feedings, and veterinary care. Pierce and Bekoff show how dogs are quick learners who are highly adaptable and opportunistic, and offer compelling evidence that dogs already do survive on their own—and could do so in a world without us.Challenging the notion that dogs would be helpless without their human counterparts, A Dog’s World enables us to understand these independent and remarkably intelligent animals on their own terms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aDogsxBehaviorxEvolution. 0aDogs-Behavior-Evolution. 0aDogs-Training. 0aDogs. 7aNATURE / Animals / Mammals.2bisacsh  aAffection.  aAlaskan Malamute.  aAllen's rule.  aAnger.  aAnxiety.  aAustralian Cattle Dog.  aBasset Hound.  aBehavior.  aBichon Frise.  aBiologist.  aBorder Collie.  aBrachycephaly.  aBreed club (dog).  aBreed club.  aBullmastiff.  aBy Nature.  aCanidae.  aCarnivore.  aComfort.  aCompanion dog.  aCompetition.  aDachshund.  aDarwin's fox.  aDog anatomy.  aDog behavior.  aDog breed.  aDog breeding.  aDog park.  aDomestication.  aDraft horse.  aEating.  aEcological niche.  aEcology.  aEcosystem.  aEmotional Intelligence.  aEndocrinology.  aEthology.  aEvolution.  aEvolutionary pressure.  aFacial expression.  aFemale.  aFennec fox.  aFood First.  aFree range.  aFree-ranging dog.  aFuture.  aGenetic diversity.  aGerman Shepherd.  aGerman Shorthaired Pointer.  aGordon Setter.  aGray wolf.  aHerding dog.  aHip dysplasia (canine).  aHome range.  aInbreeding.  aItalian Village.  aKruger National Park.  aMalware.  aMammal.  aMating preferences.  aMating.  aMetabolism.  aMixed breed.  aMother.  aNaked and Afraid.  aNatural selection.  aNeutering.  aNursing.  aOdor.  aOn the Couch (2